Notes.Title: Medium-term Scheduler Definition
Notes.Content: In main memory, certain schedulers may be selected for processes (e.g., Blocked, lower-priority) to manage specific tasks. The medium-term scheduler is responsible for swapping out processes from memory to disk and bringing processes back into memory when there is enough memory available.
Notes.Wrong_Content: In main memory, certain schedulers may be selected for processes (e.g., Blocked, lower-priority) to manage specific tasks. The medium-term scheduler is responsible for swapping out memory space and swapping in memory if there is enough memory available.

Notes.Title: Execution and System Types
Notes.Content: The execution model is centralized, and the system type is a time-sharing system.
Notes.Wrong_Content: The execution program is centralized, and the system used is a time-sharing system.

Notes.Title: Schedulers Overview
Notes.Content: There are three types of schedulers: long-term, short-term, and medium-term. The medium-term scheduler is responsible for swapping processes in and out of the main memory, thus allowing for multiprogramming and managing the degree of multiprogramming for I/O-bound and CPU-bound jobs.
Notes.Wrong_Content: There are three types of schedulers: long-term, short-term, and medium-term. The medium-term scheduler can be adjustable, allowing for multiprogramming and managing the degree of adjustable I/O-bound and CPU-bound jobs.
